# PRD Template Usage

## Template Location

The PRD template is located at `.cursor/templates/PRD Template.md` and is accessible from all projects in the workspace.

## When to Use

Use this template when:
- Transforming existing project documentation into a structured PRD format
- Creating a new PRD from scratch
- User requests to format documents as a PRD
- User asks to "transform docs into PRD format" or similar requests

## Template Structure

The PRD template follows this structure:

1. **Background** (H2)
   - Problem Statement (H3)
   - Market Opportunity (H3)
   - User Personas (H3)
   - Vision Statement (H3)
   - Product Origin (H3)

2. **Objectives** (H2)
   - SMART Goals (H3)
   - Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) (H3)
   - Qualitative Objectives (H3)
   - Strategic Alignment (H3)
   - Risk Mitigation (H3)

3. **Features** (H2)
   - Core Features (H3)
   - User Benefits (H3)
   - Technical Specifications (H3)
   - Feature Prioritization (H3)
   - Future Enhancements (H3)

4. **User Experience** (H2)
   - User Interface (UI) Design (H3)
   - User Journey (H3)
   - Usability Testing (H3)
   - Accessibility (H3)
   - Feedback Loops (H3)

5. **Milestones** (H2)
   - Development Phases (H3)
   - Critical Path (H3)
   - Review Points (H3)
   - Launch Plan (H3)
   - Post-Launch Evaluation (H3)

6. **Technical Requirements** (H2)
   - Tech Stack (H3)
   - System Architecture (H3)
   - Security Measures (H3)
   - Performance Metrics (H3)
   - Integration Requirements (H3)

## Transformation Process

When transforming existing documents into PRD format:

1. **Read the template**: Reference `.cursor/templates/PRD Template.md` to understand the structure
2. **Analyze source documents**: Review all relevant project documentation, meeting notes, user research, etc.
3. **Map content**: Match existing information to the appropriate PRD sections
4. **Fill structure**: Create a new PRD document following the template's heading hierarchy (H1, H2, H3)
5. **Preserve details**: Include all relevant information from source documents
6. **Complete sections**: Fill in all sections even if some require "TBD" or placeholder text
7. **Maintain format**: Follow the exact heading structure and formatting from the template

## Key Principles

- Always use the template structure as the foundation
- Preserve all relevant information from source documents
- Fill in sections even if information is incomplete (use placeholders when needed)
- Maintain the exact heading hierarchy (H1 for title, H2 for main sections, H3 for subsections)
- Include the Author field at the top
- Use bullet points and descriptive text as shown in the template

## Example Usage

When user says: "Transform the project docs into PRD format"

1. Read `.cursor/templates/PRD Template.md`
2. Read all relevant project documentation
3. Create a new PRD file following the template structure
4. Map existing content to appropriate sections
5. Complete all sections with available information
